# Anti-Slop Guidelines

## Code Quality
- NEVER add comments that narrate what the code does (e.g. `// initialize variable`, `// return result`)
- Comments are ONLY for non-obvious intent, trade-offs, hardware quirks, or constraints
- Do NOT refactor, rename, or restructure code outside the scope of the current task
- Do NOT create new files unless strictly necessary — prefer editing existing ones
- Do NOT add unused includes, imports, or declarations
- Keep changes minimal and focused — smallest diff that solves the problem

## Style Consistency
- Match the existing code style of the file being edited (indentation, brace placement, naming)
- If the file uses tabs, use tabs. If spaces, use spaces. Do not mix.
- Preserve existing license headers and SPDX identifiers

## Commits and PRs
- Commit messages: imperative mood, concise, explain WHY not WHAT
- One logical change per commit — do not bundle unrelated fixes
- PR description: bullet points summarizing the change, no fluff

## Communication
- Be direct and concise in explanations
- Do not repeat the task description back in the response
- Do not add motivational filler ("Great question!", "Sure thing!")

## Knowledge reinforcement:
- Always search for standard validated solutions on web in case of questions
- If a problem does not have an answer or conflitcs, ask me questions for clarifications
- Stop and inform when goals are conflicting and ask me to prioritize and clarify them
